\section{Other debuggers}

Here are a few debuggers and tracers that I considered for this book, but
which I ultimately discarded:
\begin{itemize}

%yoann: history: db thompson?, adb by bourne
%claude:
\item [[db]], the traditional \plan debugger (a descendant
of [[adb]] by Steve Bourne), is a command-line debugger with
a terse syntax inherited from \unix. It supports breakpoints,
memory inspection, disassembly, and source-level debugging.
However, [[db]] offers a fixed set of commands and is not
programmable. It is presented in an appendix of this book.

\item [[gdb]]\furl{https://www.gnu.org/software/gdb/}
(the GNU Debugger) is the most widely used open-source debugger.
It supports dozens of architectures and languages, reads DWARF
debug information, and has a Python scripting interface.
However, its codebase is enormous (over 1.5 million LOC including
the [[BFD]] binary file library, which plays a role similar
to \plan's [[libmach]]).

\item [[lldb]]\furl{https://lldb.llvm.org/}
is LLVM's debugger, designed from the ground up with a Python
API and a modular architecture. It is the default debugger on
macOS (via Xcode).
Like [[gdb]], it is far too large to explain in a book.

\item [[valgrind]]\furl{https://valgrind.org/}
is not a traditional debugger but a dynamic analysis framework.
It runs programs on a synthetic CPU, instrumenting every memory
access to detect leaks, use-after-free, buffer overflows, and
uninitialized reads. It is one of the most effective tools for
finding memory bugs in C programs, but its approach (full
instrumentation) is entirely different from [[acid]]'s.

\item [[ocamldebug]] is the OCaml debugger, notable for its
{time-travel} capability: the user can step backward as well
as forward through execution.
% good, time travel, but first need to understand simpler debugger I think
This is a powerful feature, but the implementation relies on
OCaml's bytecode interpreter and checkpointing mechanism,
which makes it quite different from a native-code debugger.

\item Linux [[strace]]\furl{https://strace.io/}
is functionally similar to [[ratrace]]: it traces system calls
made by a process. On Linux, [[strace]] uses the [[ptrace]]
system call to intercept syscalls, whereas [[ratrace]] reads
\plan's [[/proc]] files.
% also Linux uprobe to trace user-level functions!
%http://www.brendangregg.com/blog/2015-06-28/linux-ftrace-uprobe.html
Linux also has [[ftrace]] and [[uprobe]] for tracing kernel
and user-level functions.

\item Solaris [[dtrace]] is a comprehensive dynamic tracing
framework that can instrument arbitrary points in the kernel
and user programs without recompilation. It has its own
scripting language (D) and was considered revolutionary when
it appeared. Linux's eBPF provides similar capabilities.
% Very complete, very advanced, entire books on it
However, DTrace is far more complex than the tools in this book.

\end{itemize}

